 488 -    def getRndWeighted(self,listPts): 

 489          """ 
 490          From http://glowingpython.blogspot.com/2012/09/weighted-random-choice.html 
 491          Weighted random selection 
 492          returns n_picks random indexes. 
 493          the chance to pick the index i  
 494          is give by the weight weights[i]. 
 495          """ 
 496          weight = numpy.take(self.weight,listPts) 
 497          t = numpy.cumsum(weight) 
 498          s = numpy.sum(weight) 
 499          i = numpy.searchsorted(t,numpy.random.rand(1)*s)[0] 
 500          return listPts[i]

 502 -    def getLinearWeighted(self,listPts): 

 503          """ 
 504          From http://eli.thegreenplace.net/2010/01/22/weighted-random-generation-in-python/ 
 505          The following is a simple function to implement weighted random selection in Python.  
 506          Given a list of weights, it returns an index randomly, according to these weights [2]. 
 507          For example, given [2, 3, 5] it returns 0 (the index of the first element) with probability 0.2,  
 508          1 with probability 0.3 and 2 with probability 0.5.  
 509          The weights need not sum up to anything in particular,  
 510          and can actually be arbitrary Python floating point numbers. 
 511          """ 
 512          totals = [] 
 513          running_total = 0 
 514          weights = numpy.take(self.weight,listPts) 
 515          for w in weights: 
 516              running_total += w 
 517              totals.append(running_total) 
 518       
 519          rnd = random() * running_total 
 520          for i, total in enumerate(totals): 
 521              if rnd < total: 
 522                  return listPts[i]

 524 -    def getBinaryWeighted(self,listPts): 

 525          """ 
 526          From http://eli.thegreenplace.net/2010/01/22/weighted-random-generation-in-python/ 
 527          Note that the loop in the end of the function is simply looking  
 528          for a place to insert rnd in a sorted list. Therefore, it can be  
 529          speed up by employing binary search. Python comes with one built-in,  
 530          just use the bisect module. 
 531          """ 
 532          totals = [] 
 533          running_total = 0 
 534           
 535          weights = numpy.take(self.weight,listPts) 
 536          for w in weights: 
 537              running_total += w 
 538              totals.append(running_total) 
 539       
 540          rnd = random() * running_total 
 541          i = bisect.bisect_right(totals, rnd) 
 542          return listPts[i]

 544 -    def getSubWeighted(self,listPts): 

 545          """ 
 546          From http://eli.thegreenplace.net/2010/01/22/weighted-random-generation-in-python/ 
 547          This method is about twice as fast as the binary-search technique,  
 548          although it has the same complexity overall. Building the temporary  
 549          list of totals turns out to be a major part of the functions runtime. 
 550          This approach has another interesting property. If we manage to sort  
 551          the weights in descending order before passing them to  
 552          weighted_choice_sub, it will run even faster since the random  
 553          call returns a uniformly distributed value and larger chunks of  
 554          the total weight will be skipped in the beginning. 
 555          """ 
 556           
 557          weights = numpy.take(self.weight,listPts) 
 558          rnd = random() * sum(weights) 
 559          for i, w in enumerate(weights): 
 560              rnd -= w 
 561              if rnd < 0: 
 562                  return listPts[i]
